     174                 :            : // Arena allocator. Arena allocation replaces ordinary (heap-based) allocation
     175                 :            : // with new/delete, and improves performance by aggregating allocations into
     176                 :            : // larger blocks and freeing allocations all at once. Protocol messages are
     177                 :            : // allocated on an arena by using Arena::CreateMessage<T>(Arena*), below, and
     178                 :            : // are automatically freed when the arena is destroyed.
     179                 :            : //
     180                 :            : // This is a thread-safe implementation: multiple threads may allocate from the
     181                 :            : // arena concurrently. Destruction is not thread-safe and the destructing
     182                 :            : // thread must synchronize with users of the arena first.
     183                 :            : //
     184                 :            : // An arena provides two allocation interfaces: CreateMessage<T>, which works
     185                 :            : // for arena-enabled proto2 message types as well as other types that satisfy
     186                 :            : // the appropriate protocol (described below), and Create<T>, which works for
     187                 :            : // any arbitrary type T. CreateMessage<T> is better when the type T supports it,
     188                 :            : // because this interface (i) passes the arena pointer to the created object so
     189                 :            : // that its sub-objects and internal allocations can use the arena too, and (ii)
     190                 :            : // elides the object's destructor call when possible. Create<T> does not place
     191                 :            : // any special requirements on the type T, and will invoke the object's
     192                 :            : // destructor when the arena is destroyed.
     193                 :            : //
     194                 :            : // The arena message allocation protocol, required by CreateMessage<T>, is as
     195                 :            : // follows:
     196                 :            : //
     197                 :            : // - The type T must have (at least) two constructors: a constructor with no
     198                 :            : //   arguments, called when a T is allocated on the heap; and a constructor with
     199                 :            : //   a google::protobuf::Arena* argument, called when a T is allocated on an arena. If the
     200                 :            : //   second constructor is called with a NULL arena pointer, it must be
     201                 :            : //   equivalent to invoking the first (no-argument) constructor.
     202                 :            : //
     203                 :            : // - The type T must have a particular type trait: a nested type
     204                 :            : //   |InternalArenaConstructable_|. This is usually a typedef to |void|. If no
     205                 :            : //   such type trait exists, then the instantiation CreateMessage<T> will fail
     206                 :            : //   to compile.
     207                 :            : //
     208                 :            : // - The type T *may* have the type trait |DestructorSkippable_|. If this type
     209                 :            : //   trait is present in the type, then its destructor will not be called if and
     210                 :            : //   only if it was passed a non-NULL arena pointer. If this type trait is not
     211                 :            : //   present on the type, then its destructor is always called when the
     212                 :            : //   containing arena is destroyed.
     213                 :            : //
     214                 :            : // - One- and two-user-argument forms of CreateMessage<T>() also exist that
     215                 :            : //   forward these constructor arguments to T's constructor: for example,
     216                 :            : //   CreateMessage<T>(Arena*, arg1, arg2) forwards to a constructor T(Arena*,
     217                 :            : //   arg1, arg2).
     218                 :            : //
     219                 :            : // This protocol is implemented by all arena-enabled proto2 message classes as
     220                 :            : // well as RepeatedPtrField.
     221                 :            : //
     222                 :            : // Do NOT subclass Arena. This class will be marked as final when C++11 is
     223                 :            : // enabled.
